author: Michael Smith
text: It's not about the economics. Very little Huawei products (servers, receivers and comm equipment) enters US. This is about what the Intelligence discover about Huawei. Huawei, Lenovo and many Chinese companies are owned or partly owned by PLA (Peoples Liberation Army). I don't know about Huawei but I can tell you Lenovo add Keylogger chips to all their computers sold to Colleges and US Gov't agencies (Via under former name IBM PC). They use spyware for consumers. Now Oneplus can sell their phones in US because they have been vetted to not be own by PLA (Too smaller of a company). One thing all Chinese companies have to abide by is their Chinese National Intelligence Law Article 7, which states ‚Äúobligation of Chinese citizens to support national intelligence work.‚Äù However, ‚Äúit does not authorize pre-emptive spying; national intelligence work must be defensive in nature.‚Äù Example, PLA can order Oneplus to provide all data relevant to any US citizen and the Chinese Gov't will get it because Oneplus is a Chinese company. As for proof you'll never see proof from US Gov't which will expose method of detection and or source which can harm US methodology if discovered. Huawei will have no problem surviving despite what people think. OS is not that hard to create. They can get a free version of Android and integrated with their EMUI and provide their own updates or they can do what Apple has done and use Linux base OS and create their own. As for hardware they have their own hardware and doesn't require any US companies' hardware and if they need a particular hardware they can copy it just like they did before they became respectable. Just my two cents worth.

author: Onyx XI
text: I've previously owned iPhone and Samsung phones but I have to admit, from the perspective of watching entertainment on the go, Sony Xperia 1's specifications blow other phones out of the water such as Samsung S10, iPhone XS, One Plus 7 Pro etc. I will definitely be upgrading my phone to Sony Xperia 1. Let's deal with the FACTS. - Sony Xperia 1: 10-bit display (meaning it can display just over 1 billion colours) and fully unlock the potential of 100% DCI-P3 + BT2020. Competition: 8-bit display (meaning it can display just over 16 million colours). Even if the product has HDR 10+ certification, it cannot unlock the rest of the colours due to the 8-bit display limitation. Sony Xperia 1: - Has 100% DCI-P3 support along with 2020 and D65 White Point to reference better/accurate whites. - Each Sony Xperia 1 has been tuned to the Sony OLED Master Monitor which costs approximately ¬£35,000 - ¬£50,000. In an interview with Naoki Matsubara (Sony Display Engineer), he states that while OLED looks beautiful, from a film perspective, it did not have that 'film' tone before calibration hence why they had opted to calibrate it to the Sony OLED Master Monitor.

author: Bruce Goldsmith
text: @Michael Smith Michael Smith Michael Smith I personally have been with oneplus since the oneplus two, what is concerning with this whole thing is if its been done to here it can be done again and I'm more focused on the idea when the companies are targeted like this it has a ripple effect on everything else in the market today its Huawei tomorrow its someone who won't bounce back. Its just that we are finally seeing some positive trends with mid tier phones being able to match some features of the flagship devices at an affordable price and to have a setback to that change would overall hurt the consumer's choices when it comes down to price over function. Not saying there is one in phone manufacturers but a monopoly only benefits itself. I know we have more than a few choices right now but the main ones are set the market trends. Its how we got the screen ratio wars which led to various setbacks in my opinion. I personally don't use the headphone jack but it upset a lot of people who use it regularly when it went. Phones are now made thinner less robust more susceptible to breaking in order to fit a trend. Its because of a lack of new ideas that we have these trends that are marketed as what we should buy. We could be further along with battery life than we are if trends weren't the focus. Its down to the major companies being forced to come up with useful concepts rather than just trying to make minor changes seem bigger. We need new ideas. Samsung was on the right track although I don't think folding phones are the future, they still took a risk with the idea. Without competition the big companies will never have a reason to take risks and we'll pretty much stall out. Apple is already showing some signs of this with their overall sales not matching previous years. Its inevitable that if there's no push to innovate the rest will follow suit. I'm OK with the phone I currently have now, no complaints but I'm not sure where things will be when it comes time to upgrade again. I didn't think Huawei would go out of business but I do think the setback with the American market for now at least and this whole subject is going to see some changes in how things work going forward. Huawei is just an example of what could happen to other companies that may not be as fortunate. But I agree that as a company they will be alright its just going to change how they deal with the American market and how they may be viewed depending on how long this lasts and how many people will remember.

author: Fei Wang
text: Huawei has a permanent license for the ARM V8 architecture, which is the latest commercial architecture. Huawei can design processors entirely on its own, free from external constraints. Even if Huawei no longer authorizes a new version of Huawei, it can continue to develop on its own on the basis of previous versions. Other EDA chip design tools are the same. Huawei can continue to use them even if it can't continue to get new versions. This leaves time for Huawei. In fact, Huawei has other ways to avoid it, such as outsourcing. Just like you buy a car and you can rebuild the system by yourself, but after-sales is not the follow-up guarantee. This is also the time and space for Huawei to develop itself after the sale. As for Huawei system, even if Huawei does not make its own system, Google will launch Fuchsia OS. Even Samsung actually prepared its own system many years ago, but it was suspended after Google warned. You can see that Samsung's watch is using its own system, so you can see that as factories are expanding their ecosystem {car, mobile phone, computer, etc.). I'm all preparing my backup plan and I don't want to be controlled by Google all the time. I'm glad to see the birth of the ecosystem outside of iOS and Google. Huawei should be as ready as Apple to open its own developer conference. This autumn's conference is the highlight. At the same time, software and architecture authorization belong to service-oriented products. One is that there is no problem of large-scale supply, and I can continue to use them without continuing to supply them, and I have time to continue to improve them. The other is that there is no legal problem, which is also crucial. This means that Huawei's mobile phones and other products can continue to be sold smoothly in all countries of the world without being prohibited by local laws. Except for the United States, of course, they have banned Huawei's products for a long time.

author: wsl 0216
text: Overseas media comments: cracking down on Huawei to tear off the US "Enterprise Freedom" fig leaf 2019 / 05 / 22 the overseas media reported on May 22 that on the 20th, Internet giant Google has shown the extent to which American companies are obedient to White House political opinions. The Commerce Department's decision to put Huawei and its 68 affiliates on the so-called blacklist has wiped out the corporate freedom that the United States is proud of in practice. According to the Russian newspaper's website on May 21, Trump declared a state of emergency on the grounds that his information and communication system was suspected to be threatened, and his order was not yet dry, and US companies doing business with China responded hastily. Google announced that it will no longer provide some services to Huawei, which will not be able to get Android updates. It is a self-evident question of why IT, which at least ostensibly has nothing to do with the country, has suspended its long-term obligations to Huawei in order to comply with Washington's political orders. It is reported that several other US companies have followed Google's lead. Trump declared a state of emergency in the United States, allowing the government to ban domestic communications companies from buying products from foreign companies that "threaten national security," the report said. The move, first aimed at Huawei, shows once again what the White House intends to do to make the United States strong again. Mr Trump said "special threats to US national security, diplomacy and the economy" had emerged, an interpretation designed to prove the need for a state of emergency had nothing to do with reality. The typical discrimination against Huawei shows once again that the US government is doing everything it can around the world to prevent its own companies from facing competition. Russia has been treated similarly in Europe. To sell liquefied natural gas, Americans used the second line of the north stream gas pipeline to scare the old world. Washington is also asking the European Union to give up its own production of weapons for the sake of American manufacturers. According to the report, the willingness of US companies to implement White House political orders makes the agreements they have signed have no legal significance. For the White House, if the United States cannot win, there will be no "fair competition." According to an article published on the website of Hong Kong's Toutiao Daily on May 21, people used to think it was open, but it was not true. Without emergency, US President Trump signed an executive order on 15 May alleging that foreign "hostile forces" pose a national security threat to the communications system of the United States on the grounds that "the country is in a state of emergency." In fact, American companies are prohibited from doing business with Huawei in China, and they are not allowed to buy Huawei's products or sell goods or services to Huawei. Google immediately announced that it would stop some of its business with Huawei phones, the article said. When smartphones started in 2007, Apple developed its own mobile operating system, while Google developed Android, but because Google was unsuccessful in making its own phones, it opened Android to other smartphone makers. To compete with Apple's system. Google has made money from its Android app store and has developed a lucrative business. The article said that when everyone believed that Android was an open system, suddenly in a false state of emergency declared by the President of the United States, the United States could instruct Google to exclude a handset maker from Android. The so-called Libreville field (an economic theory that emphasizes market self-equilibrium and opposes government intervention) turns out to be false, as is the so-called open software system. Under the premise of Trump's "America first" and in the interests of the United States, the United States can forbid others from using what was originally open, deny free trade, and stifle business competition, even for unjustifiable reasons. The article said that this is not only, the United States more prohibited Intel, Qualcomm, Botong and other chip manufacturers to supply parts to Huawei. Similarly, with the US president's "national security", these companies can no longer supply Huawei with the aim of curbing the business and development of Huawei's mobile phones and 5G devices. The article points out that when the United States can use administrative means so directly to crack down on commercial competitors, the idea of Libreville and free trade, which the United States has always advocated, has become a big joke. It turns out that these principles will only be used when they are beneficial to the United States.

author: Abhimaneu KJ
text: To clarify the issue. 1. There is a lack of clarity about Huawei's financial structures ie we don't know who actually owns Huawei. 2. Huawei had taken money from the People‚Äôs Liberation Army, China‚Äôs National Security Commission and a third branch of the Chinese state intelligence network. 3. Huawei received an $8.5 million loan from a state-owned bank, something Huawei denies. 4. The World Bank notes that Chinese Development Bank loaned Huawei $10 billion for overseas expansion in 2004. 5. The Chinese government used Huawei‚Äôs staff to get access codes to infiltrate an unidentified foreign network. It should be noted that the accusations go back years: long before the election of US President Trump and the increasingly aggressive trade war.(To all who thinks Trump is the one who started this issue.) The other aspect of spying allegations to bear in mind is 'potential.' Much of what is said about Huawei is not about whether it spies for China or not, but rather focuses on what it 'could' do. Just like how the NSA planted backdoors in Cisco's products for years, the PLA could theoretically do the same with Huawei, it is argued.

author: Fei Wang
text: Huawei has a permanent license for the ARM V8 architecture, which is the latest commercial architecture. Huawei can design processors entirely on its own, free from external constraints. Even if Huawei no longer authorizes a new version of Huawei, it can continue to develop on its own on the basis of previous versions. Other EDA chip design tools are the same. Huawei can continue to use them even if it can't continue to get new versions. This leaves time for Huawei. In fact, Huawei has other ways to avoid it, such as outsourcing. Just like you buy a car and you can rebuild the system by yourself, but after-sales is not the follow-up guarantee. This is also the time and space for Huawei to develop itself after the sale. As for Huawei system, even if Huawei does not make its own system, Google will launch Fuchsia OS. Even Samsung actually prepared its own system many years ago, but it was suspended after Google warned. You can see that Samsung's watch is using its own system, so you can see that as factories are expanding their ecosystem {car, mobile phone, computer, etc.). I'm all preparing my backup plan and I don't want to be controlled by Google all the time. I'm glad to see the birth of the ecosystem outside of iOS and Google. Huawei should be as ready as Apple to open its own developer conference. This autumn's conference is the highlight. At the same time, software and architecture authorization belong to service-oriented products. One is that there is no problem of large-scale supply, and I can continue to use them without continuing to supply them, and I have time to continue to improve them. The other is that there is no legal problem, which is also crucial. This means that Huawei's mobile phones and other products can continue to be sold smoothly in all countries of the world without being prohibited by local laws. Except for the United States, of course, they have banned Huawei's products for a long time.

author: shao sanhei
text: Huawei self-research operating system "Hongmeng" confirmation! Android compatibility, the fastest autumn I have science and technology fantasy 05-2123:10 Huawei self-research operating system "Hongmeng" confirmation! Android compatibility, the fastest autumn Recently, the U.S. Department of Commerce listed Huawei as a "list of entities", announcing that American enterprises are prohibited from selling high-tech products to Huawei, which directly pushes Huawei "to Liangshan". After the incident, Hu Tingbo, president of Huawei Hess, wrote overnight that "Huawei spare tire chips have all been corrected", meaning that Hessi Kirin will become Huawei's main chip supplier and get rid of its dependence on American semiconductors. Soon afterwards, people became worried about switching from semiconductors to operating systems, because Google claimed that it had stopped doing some business with Huawei, and Huawei would not be able to use some of its applications in the future. What if Android didn't use them? What if you really don't use Android? In fact, the author has done such an analysis before. Huawei is the third largest smartphone manufacturer in the world, and will soon become the second largest. If Huawei cannot use Android, is it not forced to "self-supporting portal" Huawei? It's not hard for Huawei to build an operating system in its current strength, but this kind of payment has really happened, and it's hard to say that it won't need Android in the future. Huawei has to keep its hands on it. Huawei has the capital to get rid of Android's self-supporting portal. In March, Huawei's consumer CEO Yu Chengdong said that "if Huawei had to abandon Windows and Android systems and turn to internal solutions", as long as Yu Chengdong said that it was very sure, including recently Yu Chengdong also said in his circle of friends that "Huawei not only has the ability to do core work." It seems that Huawei's internal "secret weapon" is not only chips, but also systems. According to the information on the Internet, Yu Chengdong recently revealed in the group of old friends formed by famous Internet personality Fang Xingdong that as soon as this autumn and as late as next spring, Huawei's OS will probably be on the market. At the same time, Huawei's OS has opened up mobile phones, computers, tablets, televisions, cars, smart wear, and unified into an operating system. That is to say, Huawei has played a big chess game in the system, which has directly opened up many fields. More noteworthy is that Huawei's system will be compatible with Android software.

author: vietnameseloempia
text: Indeed it does feel unprecedented and very negative. As a European I want to see hard evidence and proof of claims such as made by the US about Huawei. Without hard proof it is like an economic act of war and the international community should probably sanction the US for it rather than blindly follow. Given that the US is run now by the most obviously lying, self-serving and hypocritical conman ever to be president, my suspicion is that US companies are likely doing as much spying as they claim Huawei is doing, if not more. And even if the companies themselves are not (actively) spying (more so than they are kind of open about, their business model still is to sell access to and information about their users after all), all of the world's data in the cloud is now up for grabs by US authorities under the Cloud Act. It is quite sad to see this shift from international collaboration and trust to nationalistic head bashing. But it does point out an inconvenient truth and as such may ultimately cause improvement. There need to be more options in the OS space and our entire digital lives probably should not be entrusted to a handful of companies all headquartered in the US.

author: juicebar TV
text: I think you're missing out on some very important facts. Yes, im the west we certainly do have a free market and competition. Whenever a tech company in the west releases a product or plans on doing so, it first has to get the money to start advertising it and making it look good from a competive point of view. So, conclusively, companies need to save up enough money to plan for products, make them have good quality and producing them. In China, companies like Huawei are sponsored DIRECTLY by the government of China. That basically means that the reason why they have become so famous and big in western markets is not really just because of good marketing, but because they were financially unlimited. They can do whatever they want from a financial perspective and dont need to focus on basic business aspects. Aspects, which are essentially for Western companies. If they dont have enough money, capacities and ressources to fastly build up 5G infrastructure, they cant accept the offer, whereas Huawei just goes to chinese government, asks for some millions or billions more and is just fine. Of course, this policy isnt really what I want. author: Peter Carlo Angeles
text: If you want proof that Huawei and the Chinese government are colluding, there is no bigger proof than Huawei's sudden technological leap ahead of it's competitors. This is probably due to China's forced technology transfers of companies that want to do business in the country. With it's ties to the Chinese government, it would have access to all of these technologies from different companies, giving it an edge over competitors who would only have it's own homegrown technologies to rely on. It just seems unlikely, that a new competitor would suddenly be able to develop the needed disparate technologies to outstrip other companies that have been developing the same technology for a longer time, unless they had access to breakthroughs from other companies.

author: Wayne Bell
text: China has already said it's done negotiating. It's going to wait until our next election before making any further trade negotiations in the hopes that we will have a new president that will negotiate more favorable terms. We have 532 days until we know who the president will be on Jan 20th, 2021 for the following 4 years. I have no doubt China has made preparations to sit and wait through any pain between now and Nov 3, 2020 to get a solid trade deal for a minimum of 4 years one way or the other. The US is really pushing its allies to restrict Huawei in their countries, but given the lack of evidence and rising tensions with the US, the EU is still largely planning to go ahead with Huawei 5G purchases. We will just have to wait and see where this goes, but I'm not optimistic on having a resolution until early 2021. China has a massive population and a command economy. They can manipulate their currency and shift production to other industries to weather tariffs and bans for years if need be. No one wins trade wars, but if it escalates and becomes a game of chicken to see who caves first as tariffs on both sides rise sky high, I don't think China will be the one to blink first.

author: James Donaghy
text: Yeah, Lou, it's a sticky pudding to be sure, and you're not really getting the full scoop either. Here's the thing, this ban is bullshit and it should be called out right out of the starting blocks We are, many of us, living in the Huawei 'ecosystem' as you enjoy calling it. We use their handsets and our carriers use their radio gear, and are set to develop into the next generation, the 5g network. What is the basis for banning all sprawling infrastructure? None. No basis whatsoever. You can't accuse and then act based on the complaint. You need evidence to have a case. The onus is on each of us to do the diligence for ourselves. I appreciated you've had a hard time trying to prove a negative as it were. But the fact is that no evidence exists beyond a declaration of affiliation to a country. When Apple disavow themselves from any government then you might have a point. Until that day, let's just not get tied into this hysterical ban which they have already rooled back on and which is not practical in any case. The USA may declare war on the world, but they may find themselves ignored if the world is busy moving on with tech.

author: Wayne Bell
text: Cisco and other US brands are notorious for including hidden admin accounts with user/pw built into firmware for "servicing" or "included on accident." The US Govt is known to intercept electronics to modify them with spyware and hardware backdoors. Huawei is just a pressure point for trade negotiations with China. Huawei has done everything they can to assure everyone their systems aren't compromised. They've allowed inspections, offered assurances, etc. If anything were found, they'd lose ALL their business, so it profits them nothing to include backdoors, and so far nothing has been found. Some say the very nature of 5G technology would allow Huawei to inject malware at a later date undetected, but if that's true, then so could any provider. I wouldn't put it past China to try to leverage their tech to spy on other governments, but I also know that Huawei is under a microscope and once their reputation is tarnished for spying, they won't get a 2nd chance in the marketplace which will drop them immediately. What's more important to China? Profiting from a multi-billion dollar industry or listening in on some foreign intel for a short time? I'm going to bet on the multi-billion dollar industry as being most important to their future.

text: Argument makes no sense... Despite the obvious grammatical errors, which I'll just overlook (despite your name) and assume it was just a rushed edit, and say that you need to think about the effect this has beyond the handful of Google Apps. *Enthusiast's answer would be to just root and side load those apps. All of that said - you'd still have to be an enthusiast, because the majority of the market would never go through all of that. *You'd also have to trick Google into believing you're device isn't what it is, if they decide to be dicks. But what's really at the core of this are things that we can't even know yet. We actually won't know the full implications until they release a new device (hopefully it'll never come to that). Once they've lost all of their peripherals etc. It's like saying you'd buy an iPhone, even if it had a horrible screen, slow processor, inability to connect with the radio bands needed for your ISP, slow RAM etc etc etc. This is just as much about the hardware, as it is about software. author: jqueryrocks
text: If Huawei rolls out a new OS, now it's probably a great time. I know Android may already have 1 million apps out there, but I mean come on, how many apps do you really have on your phone? I believe the apps we are using on a daily basis are mostly within the top 500 list. Plus, nowadays, a lot of apps are built with hybrid techs (PhoneGap, React Native, etc) so, it would not be so hard for app dev companies to make a new variant. Google could burn itself with this move. UPDATE: Just saw a press release from Huawei, their own OS (also open source) will be available this fall, it will compatible with all existing Android apps, so no redevelopment needed. I see some people in the replies say a new OS won't be succeeded since the MS Windows Phone failed years ago. So I need to point out that Windows Phone's failure is a result of 3 major reasons: 1) Significantly different user experience (also inferior) than iOS/Android. 2) Lacks big manufacturer support 3) Compatibility issue. Those 3 problems won't exist in Huawei's case. 1) The user experience will remain the same as their existing modified-android OS. 2) Huawei is a major player itself and highly likely we will see support from MI, OnePlus, Meizu, etc. Well, basically, all big players except Samsung and Apple. 3) Compatible with all existing Android apps. If Google doesn't allow Huawei to bundle with their apps (Gmail, Maps), just install them separately with the APK files. Maybe it will cost your extra 10 minutes. What doesn't kill you makes you stronger.

author: A S
text: You're right about the fate of Huawei Lew. And you're definitely right about the double-edged sword that Trump swings would hurt both sides. However, your hesitation about the political struggle between these two nations just reflects what US government's complicated conclusion about China - You don't know if you should eliminate this "honest" potential friend, or defend this "threat" before it's too late. The fact is, China is always an option of both. They want all the other countries to become its dependence, to accept its ridiculous totalism ideology. They could be a friend to the ones who follow this totalism ideology or a threat to the ones who didn't agree. This duality of China's global strategy made it a very difficult rival, it is both your enemy and friend at the same time. But always remember its goal had never changed - to become the only leader of the world following its own ideology. The things you mentioned, the achievement China had reached, were mostly built on its totalism ideology. Foxcon workers had suffered a lot to produce cheap and stable iPhone for the world, and Huawei workers as well. You can even found suicidal news from both of these two companies even on the Chinese newspaper in the past decades very often. If this is the cost of the global trade goal and international influence, was it worth for? So I hereby conclude as you mentioned: This is a war. But it's not only about one company, or one industry. author: Jo C
text: We have seen the same thing play out a few decades ago. .China is being put into a trade war with the US just like Japan in the 80s and 90s. During the 80s, Japan was on its way to overtake US until Washington responded by putting 100% tariffs on electronics, force voluntary restrictions on the aggressor's auto, steel, and machine industries, and adopt laws that restricted the country's steel, lumber, and sugar industries. The United States finally achieved a tactical victory in the war with the 1985 Plaza Accord when the U.S. argued that it and Japan should abandon the fixed exchange rates that had prevailed after the Second World War. The result was that U.S. imports dropped in price as the dollar fell and Japan entered the bubble economy, which would lead to the Lost Decade. Japan' economy never recovered from this. Chinese leaders have promised themselves that they won't repeat Japan's mistake. Whether it be China or the next superpower, US would do anything or find excuses to curb the next upcoming superpower.

author: Joshua Patterson
text: Recall that LTE stands for Long Term Evolution -- it was designed to be around for a long time. However, with the quick transition we had with 2G, 3G then 4G, investors and marketers pressured the industry for the next big thing. To answer, we implemented VoLT (Voice over LTE) and WiFi calling, but this wasn't enough. Then came 5G. However, 5G from a technical perspective is not feasible in the US due to the average free-space path distances and LoS limitations at the frequencies initially proposed. This is why US companies are not invested in building out 5G-it simply won't reliably work here, engineers know this. China can likely deploy it due to the population density there, but here it simply won't work except for perhaps convention centers and other high traffic locations. Also do not be fooled by AT&T's 5G network -- since the terms '2G, 3G, 4G and 5G' are not regulated, AT&T simply renamed their 4G network by calling it '5G.'

author: Joshua Son
text: This is going to make life much harder for us Americans living in China. I've been here and I speak Chinese. Having a limited understanding of the culture I can point out that almost all Chinese media and most individuals do not ever refer to themselves in the singular. Its always "We Chinese, us Chinese, the Chinese." If you have offended a mainland Chinese citizen there is a very good chance that they will explain the situation to their friends in words and writing in a way which paints your actions as an offense against all Chinese people. The culture here pushes people to identify as a group and not as individuals. This will have me answering questions like "Do all Americans hate the Chinese?" or responding to comments telling me to get out of their country for months. This is going to actively affect the lives of American expats in China. So fucking thank you Trump.

author: Hard Way
text: As SW engineer, yes it is complicated to identify if a system have "back door", but there are no magic in engineer, every signal send can record, every packet transmit can be traced, which port is open, what socket is send/recv , what is inside packet all can be traced and analyzed. Software and hardware is human product guided by specific rules and law of physics, every product I saw always have bugs, through these bugs, venerability exposed, sometime it is hard to say it is a human error or did it on purpose. Communication equipment just like highway , its job is efficiently deliver packets from any source to any destination as quickly as possible, if you don't want others to see you have sex in the car on highway, don't build your car transparent, it is application's job to ensure your data encrypted checksummed , don't send plain text content, anybody can capture the wireless signal and analyze the packet if they are not encrypted. In that sense Huawei's role in information security is overstated. I have no doubt this is just extend of America First policy, kill approaching second is one way to ensure first. The spirt of Law , innocent until proven guilty, The spirt of free and liberty , competition achieve excellency. All doesn't matter in the font of America first. author: Antonio Guarnaschella
text: Still watching, but I'll try to comment as I go. The problem with banning Apple from China is something that can't be done because of 3 reasons: 1- Banning Apple in China will force one of the biggest electronic manufacturer on the planet to fire tens of thousands of people, and we are talking of a market where the government promised that will always give jobs to people. 2- Foxconn IS NOT a Chinese manufacturer is a Taiwanese one, Taiwan can easily use their Indian (not sure if they're up and running yet) factories to manufacture iPhones only since they own the technology that makes them already. 3- China is a country based on face, iPhone is a status symbol, having the latest iPhone is the way to really flex on other people. Take that away and the people would not be happy. I'm an expat living in China, so I can see how and what is going on and, even if I'm not American, I can understand where the trade war and all this problems come from. This measures come after China declined and revised the entire trade agreement, while up in the US they used to have a real free market until some months ago. Is not easy to comment on this without getting super political, but in all honesty this can go only in 2 ways. 1- fix everything when China finally decides to follow an agreement 2- get your rifle ready, because it will go down pretty pretty fast.. As for competition, I can't speak about NA in general, but in Europe Huawei has been a major player since forever albeit in the high/mid and not the flagship segment. That also can help you understand how Europe is reacting As for the Government implication, I think that the USA is using the classic "eye for an eye" policy...as for 5G..do we really need it? In Italy (where I'm from) is already a miracle if we get 4G in some areas...

author: MAANI IBLIS
text: It sucks for Huawei. The US ban will compromise the company's dealings with many of the services provided by other companies based in the United States including Google and the android platform on smartphones set to release later this year. We are to blame for the rise of Chinese manufacturing prowess. Many American companies began manufacturing in China giving incentives to China to partner up for mutual benefit where they supply the cheap labor while building industries. This allowed for Chinese manufacturing to advance at a faster pace especially considering the population. The Chinese government has made sure that they have Chinese people who are working in these factories. Here is a harsh truth nobody seems to want to admit: corporate espionage is practiced daily by companies from all different countries and government espionage is a certainty. China has abetted companies who have stolen intellectual property and patents. An example is Microsoft Windows being used without licensing from Microsoft, in China... Would you have trouble saying I'm not buying crude oil from Putin even though my society is in desperate need of gasoline from Russia if that were the case? My honest opinion is that most people wouldn't support money going to Putin. The double standard applies here only because the difference is we have a better idea of the inner workings of the Russian government, and are ignorant of the inner workings of the Chinese government. We therefore are left thinking that China is the place where most of "my products" come from that save me money plus there stuff is as good as Japanese stuff used to be... This isn't the actual case. Let's look at what the standards for an employee are as an employee in Japan versus China, world's of differences as well as regulatory practices and laws. In the end it comes down to this: if Putin was pushing for Russian currency to become the World monetary currency people would rail that he is a corrupt enemy dictator. Tanks running over students during protests... all forgotten, at least now you can leave Russia much more easily than the USSR, leave China and you are considered a Chinese asset abroad by the Chinese government akin to the glorious KGB days of the USSR. I don't trust Huawei, Samsung, Apple, Google... Governments they will use your information and they will spy and companies want opportunities to make more money and will use personal info. You see my family came here from Russia after living under the communist regime. My friends from China are not so endeared to China. China shows the same propensities as the USSR in exertion of its perceived borders. If I wouldn't trust Putin and wouldn't want Russian currency to become the world monetary currency I wouldn't want the alternatively better organized Communist dictatorship to have their currency placed instead of Russia. I believe communist ideology antithetical to the way our societies wish to function. Communism is yet another anachronism in our society. Canadian companies including BlackBerry have had issues with vulnerabilities from way back. Companies including Huawei and other suppliers of Canadas 4G equipment and antennas have had backdoors found and dealt with behind closed doors by companies buying the products. The telecom Giants, the big 3, have hidden some of the shadier practices behind closed boardroom doors. Huawei had once been in a particular instance in Italy, that recently noted how there was a lengthy dialogue surrounding the backdoors found in their telecommunications equipment and how there were multiple instances of such behavior and how long it took to resolve. The fact is that Huawei was pretty shady and didn't immediately fulfill promises to remove backdoors. If it were leaked that these instances have been repeated when the Huawei tech was under scrutiny in many other countries by telecom companies making purchases for 4G networks, people would be very unhappy. Unfortunately telecommunications companies are trying to make billions and don't want to spend more money to begin their 5G networks, hence they will likely be untruthful and downplay the threat possibilities and deny that they have in some instances found vulnerabilities related to backdoors but resolved the issue in private in a manner they found acceptable. We tend to be a society based on perception rather than truth and the belief that a good PR campaign can cure the perception the public has of a particular thing in any instance. We rely heavily on Chinese products so hopefully our "devil's" ('elected' political leaders)will work out the trade war and we will have a deal. Huawei being put in the penalty box is ok if you are playing the same game, hopefully it will not be long before resolution is found.

author: Ë∞¢ÊòäÂ§©
text: Someone brought up a point that the existence of Samsung destroys the argument that the US kills foreign companies competing with the US ones. Have a look at this link https://www.samsung.com/global/ir/stock-information/ownership-structure/ If you look at Samsung‚Äôs ownership structure, you can see that Samsung has the majority of their stock held by foreign investors, more specifically people/organizations on Wall Street, like Citi group, Morgan Stanley etc. The reason why Samsung isn‚Äôt banned and is allowed access to core technologies is obvious, it is basically American. Unlike Huawei, which is not a publicly traded company, and therefore is 100% privately owned by Chinese, consequently the US has literally 0 control over. If you wonder why it is this way, I‚Äôll let you in on some history, after the 1997 Asian economic crisis, which was caused by the US to suppress economic growth in Asian countries like Korea, Samsung was broken into many subsidiaries and sold off to pay off their debt. For instance their heavy industrial department was sold to Volvo, Pharmaceutical department to Johnson Wax, LED to GE etc. after taking into account all the cross holding of interest, 55% of the current Samsung conglomerate is foreign, and mostly American. It was only after it is Americanized, it successfully globalized, whereas despite of its massive influence in Korea before the crisis, it was never truly global and never pierced into the most technologically advanced industries as one of the top contenders. If you look at globally successful companies in Asia, especially the biggest ones of a certain country/region like Mitsubishi of Japan, TSMC of Taiwan, Samsung of S Korea etc. they almost always had their controlling interest being American, or else they wouldn‚Äôt be allowed by the US to become anything significant. And those companies, like Samsung, also became American after a US caused economic crisis. Except in China, where the biggest companies are either state owned or Chinese owned and successfully survived multiple economic crisis basically unscathed. I‚Äôll let you figure of why the US is so afraid China and want to takedown Huawei at the risk of losing their hypocritical outlook of righteousness. Huawei might not succeed, but it is a martyr, and it‚Äôs legacy will be significant and meaningful for any non-American own companies forward.

author: Gu Yewen
text: Good video Lew. To be honest, I am not worried about Huawei too much. Will they slow down their growth, yes. Will they shut down? No. The main reason Huawei can have a fight in this game is that the market in China is so big. 60% of the 4G stations on this planet are in China and this number may be even higher with 5G. Also the one of the largest smart phone market. I am from China and have been to US and Europe and I know the 4G coverage difference between the west and China, especially in rural area. So even if Huawei just serve the demand in China only, it will be just fine. And of couse, it got many EU and south east asia and middle east orders. The smartphone department is actually affacted least in this US bullying. The chip design tool you mentioned, there are some open source tool which is less efficient than the US ones but free to use. Other banned chips can be sourced else where too, but much less advanced of course. Some produced locally in China already. But with Huawei such a new big customer, the stock price of these local chip producers in China skyrocket these days. And it is possible they will invest more in R&D with the money from Huawei and become more advanced in the future. The key issue is the laptop department. Huawei laptop actually grows very quick these years. But without Intel or AMD. It is pretty dead for now. But there is very strong discussion that Huawei may release its own OS since no one will buy its phone without GOOGLE PLAY anyway. And at least the local apps in China will 100% sure adapt to this OS due to the government presure. In the oversea market, it is hard to say. Therefore, there may be laptop with kirin chips and Huawei OS in the future, just like the macs. You cant imagine the national sentiment in China about Huawei now. Their share in EU will go down, but their share in China will go further up.

author: Ë∞¢ÊòäÂ§©
text: Master Sherpa https://www.samsung.com/global/ir/stock-information/ownership-structure/ If you look at Samsung‚Äôs ownership structure, you can see that Samsung has the majority of their stock held by foreign investors, more specifically people/organizations on Wall Street, like Citi group, Morgan Stanley etc. The reason why Samsung isn‚Äôt banned and is allowed access to core technologies is obvious, it is basically American. Unlike Huawei, which is not a publicly traded company, and therefore is 100% privately owned by Chinese, consequently the US has literally 0 control over. If you wonder why it is this way, I‚Äôll let you in on some history, after the 1997 Asian economic crisis, which was caused by the US to suppress economic growth in Asian countries like Korea, Samsung was broken into many subsidiaries and sold off to pay off their debt. For instance their heavy industrial department was sold to Volvo, Pharmaceutical department to Johnson Wax, LED to GE etc. after taking into account all the cross holding of interest, 55% of the current Samsung conglomerate is foreign, and mostly American. It was only after it is Americanized, it successfully globalized, whereas despite of its massive influence in Korea before the crisis, it was never truly global and never pierced into the most technologically advanced industries as one of the top contenders. If you look at globally successful companies in Asia, especially the biggest ones of a certain country/region like Mitsubishi of Japan, TSMC of Taiwan, Samsung of S Korea etc. they almost always had their controlling interest being American, or else they wouldn‚Äôt be allowed by the US to become anything significant. And those companies, like Samsung, also became American after a US caused economic crisis. Except in China, where the biggest companies are either state owned or Chinese owned and successfully survived multiple economic crisis basically unscathed. I‚Äôll let you figure of why the US is so afraid China and want to takedown Huawei at the risk of losing their hypocritical outlook of righteousness.
